{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529795"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:58:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:58:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14459"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14459"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.47,0.04,0.04,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7154"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112507"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7154"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14459"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94541"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"7984"},{"type":"tags","id":"8758"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17091"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17092"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34997"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36174"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37553"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37596"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112507"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-year history of intermittent pain, swelling and discharge from her armpits. Each episode may last about a week and usually resolves with topical antiseptics and warm compresses. The current episode has not responded to her usual home remedies. She has a medical history of obesity (BMI 31 kg/m2) and type 2 diabetes, for which she takes metformin. She has a 15 pack-year smoking history and drinks two glasses of wine a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 118/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. Inspection of her axillae is demonstrated below(Image). There are no other abnormal findings.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral clindamycin and rifampicin","Oral flucloxacillin","Photodynamic therapy","Oral infliximab","Surgery with healing by secondary intention"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic signs and symptoms of hidradenitis suppurativa (HS), a chronic inflammatory condition primarily affecting the apocrine gland-bearing areas of the body, most commonly the axillae and groin from puberty to young adulthood. The recurrent nature of the symptoms, age, the location, and the presence of risk factors (obesity, smoking) all support this diagnosis. The presence of sinus tract formation and scarring with recurrent lesions indicates Hurley stage 2 disease, which requires more aggressive treatment than stage 1. The scarring can be psychologically damaging and lead to restrictions in movement or lymphoedema in severe cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Hurley classification is the grading system for HS. It categorises HS as stage I (single or multiple abscesses, no sinus tracts or scarring), stage II (recurrent single or multiple abscesses with sinus tracts and scarring, and widely separated lesions) or stage III (diffuse or almost diffuse involvement or multiple interconnected tracts and abscesses).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral clindamycin and rifampicin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line therapy for this patient with moderate (Hurley stage 2) HS inflammatory flare. Systemic antibiotics are indicated when topical treatments have failed or when there are multiple lesions with scarring or sinus tract formation. Oral clindamycin 300mg twice daily with rifampicin 600mg daily is recommended for their antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties. Lifestyle modifications such as smoking cessation, wearing loose clothing to prevent occlusion and weight loss are crucial for long-term management. For women, hormonal therapy with combined oral contraceptive pills or spironolactone may also be beneficial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral flucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not the recommended antibiotic regimen for hidradenitis suppurativa though would be appropriate for uncomplicated cellulitis. While it may help with secondary bacterial infections, it does not address the underlying inflammatory process of HS. The combination of clindamycin and rifampicin has been shown to be more effective due to their combined antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhotodynamic therapy\u003C/strong\u003E involves the application of a photosensitizing agent followed by light exposure. While it has shown some promise in small studies for HS, it is not considered first-line therapy and is generally reserved for cases that have not responded to conventional treatments. Evidence for its efficacy in HS is limited, and it may not be readily available in all clinical settings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral infliximab\u003C/strong\u003E, a tumour necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-\u03b1) inhibitor, is a biological therapy that can be effective in severe, refractory HS. However, it is typically considered a third-line treatment after failure of antibiotics and other systemic therapies and under dermatology review. It also carries risks of serious side effects and requires careful patient selection and monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgery with healing by secondary intention\u003C/strong\u003E is an option for severe, persistent HS that has not responded to medical management. However, it is not the first-line approach and is usually reserved for chronic, scarred areas or recurrent abscesses. Surgery can be associated with significant morbidity and does not prevent recurrence in uninvolved areas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMetformin, the combined oral contraceptive pill, spirolactone and finasteride are also considered as adjuncts alongside lifestyle management. Dermatology opinion should be requested early for this chronic disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hidradenitis suppurativa is a chronic inflammatory condition commonly affecting the axillae and groin, associated with obesity, diabetes, and smoking.","First-line systemic therapy for moderate (Hurley stage 2) hidradenitis suppurativa is oral clindamycin and rifampicin.","Management of hidradenitis suppurativa requires a multidisciplinary approach including lifestyle modifications and medical therapy."],"references":["Vekic DA. Hidradenitis suppurativa \u2013 Management, comorbidities and monitoring. Aus Fam Phys 2017; 46:584-88.  Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2017/august/hidradenitis-suppurativa-management-comorbidities","Van Straalen K et al, Insights into hidradenitis suppurativa. Journal of Allergy and Clinial Immunology, 2002: 149 (4).  Available at: https://www.jacionline.org/article/0091-6749(22)00220-2/fulltext","Smith S et al. Management of hidradenitis suppurativa: an Australasian consensus statement | DermNet NZ [Internet]. dermnetnz.org. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/hidradenitis-suppurativa-guidelines","Dagenet C, Lee KH, Sayed C, et al. Comprehensive and\u00a0Updated Algorithm of\u00a0Hidradenitis Suppurativa Management from\u00a0the\u00a0Experts. Am J Clin Derm 2025; 26:487\u201397 .https://doi.org/10.1007/s40257-025-00940-0"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94541"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14459"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21093"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21093"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8eNfEInvJgkhj0mJ9ySC1Rq1yADIT3.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8eNfEInvJgkhj0mJ9ySC1Rq1yADIT3.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":941,"height":1500}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94541"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-02T08:40:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-02T08:40:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7154"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112507"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/